post_text:
NEW ONLINE FORMS

We are very excited to announce that Preble Shawnee Schools has partnered with FinalForms, an online forms and data management service that will be replacing paper forms. FinalForms allows parents of new students to enroll their children online. It also allows parents of current students to complete and sign back-to-school and athletic participation forms online. The most exciting news is that FinalForms saves data from season-to-season and year-to-year, meaning that you will never need to enter the same information twice! FinalForms also pre-populates information wherever possible, for each of your students, saving you time.

Parents should be receiving an email from‚Ä¶

post_text:
Preble Shawnee Local Education Association 2019-2020 Scholarship

For the 2019-2020 school year, the PSLEA will be awarding two $500 scholarships to graduating Shawnee students. To apply, please respond to the following question in the form of a 2-3 page essay.

Where do you see yourself in five years, and how has Preble Shawnee helped prepare you for this goal?

Please submit a word or google document to psleaunion@gmail.com by June 22, 2020. In order to maintain anonymous voting, members of the PSLEA will vote on the responses after all identifying information has been removed from the documents. Winners will be notified via the email used for their submission on June 29, 2020.

post_text:
SPECIAL BOARD MEETINGS ANNOUNCED

There will be two Special Board of Education Meetings on Thursday, June 4, 2020 and Tuesday, June 9, 2020 both at 6:00 p.m. in the Camden Primary Gymnasium. Please enter through the gymnasium doors off the parking area near the Board of Education Office.

The purpose of the meeting is to hold a public hearing on the matter of the possible closing of West Elkton Intermediate School either prior to, during, or at the conclusion of the 2020-21 school year. The Board of Education will give the rationale for such a move and would like to hear from the public for feedback.

Seating will be spaced to allow for physical distancing recommendations. We will also live stream the meeting with Public Participation via phone available by calling 937-452-1283 and pressing 1 when prompted at the correct time for commentary.

GRADUATION UPDATE

This email was sent to the Class of 2020 via email this afternoon.

Seniors,

This afternoon I, along with superintendents from each Preble County School District, met with Preble County Health Commissioner Erik Balster regarding options for our graduation ceremony. His department has provided guidance on additional options to consider not previously available. I ask for your patience as the administration works through some of the information as quickly as we can. We would like to announce the new plan in the next few days.

As we work through some of the details, Mrs. Whitis and I would like to have several seniors volunteer to give input on the initial draft. If you are‚Ä¶

GRADUATION CEREMONY

We will be posting a communication on Monday, May 18th on revised graduation ceremony plans for the Class of 2020.
Enhancements will include:
1) Flexible times for seniors to schedule their appointment that will also include dates in early June
2) Options for seniors with larger families
3) Stadium graduation ceremony opportunity in June or July (if permitted by the Ohio Department of Education)

post_text:
SUMMER MEAL SIGN UP

Meals will be available all summer for Preble Shawnee students through Preble County Summer Cafe. Please share this information so families can sign up. There are three easy ways for parents to register:

1. Visit their website at http://summercafe.org/
2. Text "cafe" to 937-400-1767
3. Visit their Facebook page which has links for registration https://www.facebook.com/PCSummerCafe

Preble Shawnee will continue to distribute food on Wednesdays, however, May 20th will be our last distribution day. To receive meals through the summer, please sign up for this opportunity.

post_text:
GRADING FOR FOURTH QUARTER

I wanted to speak to our students and parents about the Remote Learning Assignments and fourth quarter grades. As previously communicated, we have provided a safety net for students in grades 7-12 to receive a grade no lower than their first, second, and third quarter average. Students in grades K-6 will receive met or not met expectations. Both are available for students completing work. However, we are seeing cases where no work is being turned in. Students not completing any assignments run the risk of failing the fourth quarter. For grades 7-12, this could potentially impact final grades, credits, and athletic eligibility for the fall. Please reach out to your child‚Äôs teacher or principal if you have yet to complete assignments and let‚Äôs finish this school year strong.

-Dr. Matt Bishop, Superintendent

http://www.psarrows.com/protected/ArticleView.aspx?iid=63AGPI0&dasi=4GPAI

FROM THE UNITED WAY (PREBLE COUNTY OFFICE)

The COVID-19 crisis has impacted all of us and, now more than ever, we need our community to stand in the gap for UWGDA, our partners and the people we serve on a daily basis. Below is some information to share on ways to get help or to give help.

If You Need Help

‚Ä¢ HelpLink 211 operates 24/7/365 as a resource for anyone struggling to meet basic needs, financial obligations or looking for information on available health and human services.

‚Ä¢ The Familywize prescription card is a free card providing an average of 45% savings on prescription drugs. You can download the card here.

On Monday, April 20th, Governor Mike DeWine officially closed Ohio public schools for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year. All buildings and athletic facilities will remain closed, except for essential personnel. This is necessary to prevent widespread infection of the coronavirus. In anticipation of Governor DeWine‚Äôs announcement, we have been working on this update to inform our students, families and staff.

FINAL VOTING INFORMATION! PLEASE READ!
(thank you to the folks at Camden Comeback for posting this information)

If you need information about the Bond Issue or Income Tax, please visit www.psarrows.com.

Per the Preble County Board of Elections...if you have applied for a ballot to vote and have not received it, you can still vote! You will need to pick up a Provisional Ballot at the Preble County Board of Elections and return it/mail it to Eaton by the deadlines. (Please note: the return guidelines below also pertain to those who have received their ballots but not yet returned them.)

1. Call the Preble County Board of Elections at (937) 456-8117 to let them know you are on your way to pick‚Ä¶

post_text: We strongly suggest that you take your Absentee Ballot request straight to the Board of Elections Office at the Courthouse. You can use the walk up window on the east side alley. post_text: Governor DeWine announced this afternoon that we will not be returning to school for the rest of this school year. We will continue with our Remote Learning Assignments. We will be working on one more distribution to get us through the end of the year. Details will be forthcoming. Spring athletics will be cancelled as a result of this decision. We will still need guidance for events such as graduation and prom that have large numbers of people attending in close quarters. We will communicate details of those events when we know more. For our students and seniors, we wish the circumstances We find ourselves in were different. When given the opportunity, we will make sure the events that are left will be memorable. Please continue to visit our website www.psarrows.com for information.

UPDATE FOR 4/17/20

Grading:
There is important grading information regarding the Remote Learning Assignments for grades K-12 on our website www.psarrows.com. The information was also sent to all student email accounts.

8th Grade Annual Washington D.C. Trip:
Due to the current social distancing requirements, it is necessary to reschedule the DC Trip (again). The new dates of the trip will be November 3-7, 2020. These dates were selected as they do not conflict with game schedules for those involved in extracurricular activities. If something should happen and there be a resurgence in COVID-19 cases, the trip will take place March 23-27, 2021. We are committed to providing this experience for our students. Thank you for your understanding.

Parent Questionnaire (Preschool and Students with Special Needs)

Please click on the link below. The information collected will determine how we deliver instruction, should the closure extend beyond April 6, 2020. From the Register-Herald

Statement from Ohio Governor Mike DeWine on the March 17, 2020 Election
(COLUMBUS, Ohio)‚ÄîGovernor DeWine announced tonight the following:

"During this time when we face an unprecedented public health crisis, to conduct an election tomorrow would force poll workers and voters to place themselves at a unacceptable health risk of contracting coronavirus. As such, Health Director Dr. Amy Acton will order the polls closed as a health emergency. While the polls will be closed tomorrow, Secretary of State Frank LaRose will seek a remedy through the courts to extend voting options so that every voter who wants to vote will be granted that opportunity."

My advice...when you wake up tomorrow, check out the news and make sure there really isn‚Äôt an Election going on. -Supt Matt Bishop

Several people have inquired about possibly donating items to the effort to feed all Preble County students. Donations will be received tomorrow...see below.

The Preble County Success Liaisons and United Way, in conjunction with the Common Good of Preble County, will be assembling breakfast and lunch food packs to distribute throughout the county for students since they are out of school.

Packs are being assembling tomorrow at the Nazarene Church, 201 E. Lexington Road, between the hours of 1-4 p.m. The plan is to give 7 days of breakfast and lunch food to students each week and they hope to make 550 bags tomorrow to distribute on Wednesday.

They are in need of REUSABLE GROCERY BAGS to send the food out to families. If you have any available, please drop them off at the church during donation hours tomorrow.

COVID-19 UPDATE
March 15, 2020

Just a reminder, schools will be closed until we return from Spring Break on Monday, April 6th. All activities are cancelled. This includes the use of all facilities, both indoor and outdoor.

Representatives from all Preble County Schools are meeting Monday afternoon to finalize our plan to provide meals for our students during this closure. We will make those plans known on social media and our website.

Circumstances are changing by the day. We are hopeful we will return in a few weeks. I realize Governor DeWine hinted at a potential further closure. We will continue to make plans to provide the best educational opportunity possible under the circumstances.

Please go to www.psarrows.com for the latest information.

GO ARROWS!

Dr. Matt Bishop, Superintendent

post_text:
A paper has been circulating through the community with incorrect information. It states the levy "would increase property taxes on a home valuation of 100,000 by $375.00 a year." This is absolutely FALSE.

Property taxes are assessed at 35% of valuation...meaning, only $35,000 of a $100,000 home would be assessed the 3.75 mills.

$35,000 multiplied by .00375 = $131.25 annually or $10.94 monthly.

Please get up to date on the FACTS of this levy. We posted our Levy FAQ's in a post earlier today. Also, you can visit our website for more information. The link is below.

We want to remind our voters, Preble Shawnee has the lowest combined school property and income tax rates of all Preble County‚Ä¶

What will happen the morning after Election Day (March 17th) if the levies pass?

We will make two phone calls that morning. The first call will be to our Construction Manager who will oversee the renovation of our Jr/Sr High School. We will let them know we are ready to order the mechanical systems (i.e. boilers, air handles, unit ventilators) that require extra time to order and have ready to begin installation once students and staff leave for the summer. The renovation includes replacing the boilers, unit ventilators, air handles, electrical, lighting, stadium lighting, ceiling tiles, and plumbing. We will fund this renovation with between $4-6.5 million dollars of our existing carryover.‚Ä¶ More

How did we decide on the two ballot issues facing Preble Shawnee voters on March 17th?

Last year, our district embarked on a comprehensive community engagement process. The purpose was to recommend a facilities master plan to our Board of Education. Preble Shawnee Schools contracted with SHP Leading Design to facilitate the endeavor. We worked alongside the Ohio Facilities Construction Commission (OFCC) to evaluate our available co-funding options with the state.

A Community Advisory Team met many times throughout the 2018-19 school year. The group was comprised of many community members with differing viewpoints on the best way to achieve our facility goals.

In addition to our advisory‚Ä¶

post_text:
FOOD PANTRIES NOW AVAILABLE FOR STUDENTS

We are pleased to announce we now have two food pantries located at our Jr/Sr High School. We were able to make this happen by partnering with The Common Good of Preble County and the Foodbank. The pantry will be restocked by food from the Foodbank each month. They will be open at all times during the school day. There are a variety of breakfast items, snacks and quick meals that students can make on their own as well as some household and hygiene items. We have been working on this project for a while and are very excited that it is now available to our students. This project was coordinated by our Success Liaison Christine Wilson.

post_text:
NEW SECURITY DOORS ADDED THROUGH GRANT

Recently, Preble Shawnee applied for and received a safety grant from the Ohio Bureau of Workers‚Äô Compensation. We were able to purchase additional entry doors for both Camden Primary and West Elkton Intermediate. The grant provided three dollars for every dollar Preble Shawnee spent on the project. With the installation of these doors, visitors now must enter the offices of each building and will not have open access to the building.

Our next focus will be at the Jr/Sr High School. Part of the proposed renovation this summer would be converting an existing classroom near the front doors into a new entrance for parents and visitors. This new office will house the attendance secretary and the School Resource Officer. This will limit access to the building just like Camden Primary and West Elkton Intermediate.

With the addition of the new doors, School Resource Officers in each building, and other safety enhancements, we are providing a safe learning and working environment for our students, staff, and families.

#ProudToBePrebleShawnee

post_text:
On Friday, August 30th, 2019, the PBIS Tier 1 Team orchestrated a pep rally for the Preble Shawnee Jr./Sr. High. The student body competed in minute-to-win-it style games. The goal of the pep rally was to kick off the school year with a positive lead, to promote team building, and support one another. The winning target teams for Jr. High and High School were awarded trophies, crafted by Ms. Lawson, which have been proudly displayed in their respected target time classrooms.

The Tier 1 Team (consisting of Mrs. Hoeffel, Mr. Mann, Mr. Schmidt, Ms. Lawson, Mr. Wright, Mrs. Whitis, Mr. Ellis, and Miss Bauerschmidt) looks forward to organizing future events promoting positive behavior and character.

-Tier 1 Team

FINAL FOUR STATE TENNIS

Pierce Elliott advances to the OHSAA State Tennis Semi-Finals with 6-1, 7-5 win this afternoon. He will compete tomorrow morning at 9 a.m. at the Lindner Family Tennis Center in Mason for a chance to become Preble Shawnee High Schools second State Champion.

Good luck Pierce!

#FinalFour
#ProudToBePrebleShawnee
